    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Sept. 28<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1878</date>
                    <seg type="supplemental"><hi rend="italic">Private</hi> </seg>
                    <salute>Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I enclose a copy of the “Medium” with an account of the detection of Williams the Spiritualist. I am in hopes that you may think it worth while to publish the exposure of a person who has imposed on the public with such success for so many years—<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>Sir. Your obedient servant | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1"><hi rend="italic">0.3 Private</hi>] <hi rend="italic">in CD’s hand</hi></note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n2">2.1 Sir. … Darwin] <hi rend="italic">in CD’s hand</hi> </note>
            </div>

             
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-11699.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to G. J. Romanes, 21 September [1878]</ref>. A letter in the <hi rend="italic">Spiritualist</hi>, 20 September 1878, p. 133, described the finding of false beards, muslin, ribbons, phosphoric acid, and an instrument for writing on sealed slates on the persons of the mediums <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_7021.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Charles E. Williams</ref> and Mr <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_8281.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">A. Rita</ref> at a séance in Amsterdam. CD presumably reversed the words ‘Medium’ and ‘Spiritualist’ in his first sentence in error. The <hi rend="italic">Medium and Daybreak</hi>, another spiritualist newspaper, ran a story about the affair on 27 September 1878, but they supported Williams and Rita and included statements from the two men claiming that they had been entrapped.</note>
        </div>
    
